&quot; The obvious answer is that the common ground of family values, conservative politics, and banning gay marriage overcomes little things like the principles of faith.&quot;
As I think was at least alluded to in the comments to the previous post, I think it is more subtle than that. What you list applies to many protestant groups as well. But with Mormons, there is also commonality in (1) having a religion with a fairly complicated and obscure-to-outsiders set of rules &lt;i&gt;and practices&lt;/i&gt;, about which one has been the target of ill-will and persecution in the recent past and for which one therefore mostly wants to be left alone (by both secularists and evangelicals) rather than evangelize/publicize, and (2) being a (generally) white-looking religious minority (seemingly?) overrepresented in the well-paying professions.
(I realize the mormom mission goes against what i say re: &quot;rather than evangelize,&quot; but I think it is still true that in american politics mormons have a &quot;leave us and our peculiarities alone&quot; streak rather than a &quot;be like us and adopt our pecluiarities&quot; streak.)
